# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: grafana-loki
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is distributed and uses JSON documents stored in indices divided into shards, each of which may have replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] It supports full-text search, faceted search, real-time search, and multitenancy.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] The software is developed alongside Logstash, Kibana, and Beats as part of the Elastic Stack (formerly the ELK Stack).
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Shay Banon created the precursor to Elasticsearch, called Compass, in 2004.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Developing a third version of Compass, he concluded that a full rewrite was necessary to build a scalable, distributed search solution using JSON over HTTP as a common interface.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] He released the first version of Elasticsearch in February 2010.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Elastic NV was founded in 2012 to provide commercial services and products around Elasticsearch and related software.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] In June 2014, the company raised $70 million in a Series C funding round led by New Enterprise Associates, with additional funding from Benchmark Capital and Index Ventures, bringing total funding to $104 million.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] In March 2015, the company changed its name from *Elasticsearch* to *Elastic* and, through the acquisition of Found, launched a managed cloud offering later known as Elastic Cloud.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] In November 2017, Elastic acquired the search startup Swiftype, whose technology became the basis for Elastic App Search and Elastic Site Search.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Elastic also formed partnerships with Google to offer Elastic Cloud on Google Cloud Platform and with Alibaba to offer Elasticsearch and Kibana on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] In June 2018, Elastic filed for an initial public offering with an estimated valuation of between $1.5 and $3 billion.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] On 5 October 2018, Elastic was listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] In January 2021, Elastic announced that starting with version 7.11, Elasticsearch and Kibana would be relicensed from Apache License 2.0 to a dual license under the Server Side Public License and the Elastic License, neither of which is recognised as an open-source license.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Elastic stated the change was a response to Amazon Web Services (AWS) offering Elasticsearch and Kibana as a service without what Elastic described as adequate collaboration.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Critics of the change noted that Elastic had previously promised never to alter the Apache 2.0 licensing of Elasticsearch, Kibana, Beats, and Logstash, and predicted the move would damage the ecosystem.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] AWS responded by announcing a fork of the projects to continue development under Apache License 2.0.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Other members of the Elasticsearch ecosystem, including Logz.io, CrateDB, and Aiven, also committed to supporting a fork.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Due to potential trademark conflicts with the name "Elasticsearch", AWS rebranded their fork as OpenSearch in April 2021.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] In August 2024, Elastic added the GNU Affero General Public License as a third licensing option for Elasticsearch starting with version 8.16.0.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] This made the software available under a free and open-source license once again alongside the two source-available options.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is built on Apache Lucene and exposes Lucene's capabilities through a JSON and Java API.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Documents are stored in indices, which are divided into primary shards; each shard may have zero or more replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Routing and rebalancing are handled automatically.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Once an index has been created, the number of primary shards cannot be changed.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] The engine supports faceted search and percolation, a form of prospective search in which stored queries are matched against incoming documents rather than the reverse.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] A gateway module handles long-term index persistence, allowing an index to be recovered after a node failure.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Real-time GET requests make Elasticsearch usable as a NoSQL datastore, though it does not support distributed transactions.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] In May 2019, Elastic made the core security features of the Elastic Stack available without charge, including TLS for encrypted communications, file and native realm authentication, and role-based access control for cluster APIs and indices.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] The corresponding source code is available under the Elastic License.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch also offers SIEM and machine learning capabilities as part of its commercial offerings.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Official client libraries are maintained for Java, C# (.NET), PHP, Python, and Ruby, among others.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is developed alongside Logstash (a data collection and log-parsing engine), Kibana (an analytics and visualisation platform), and Beats (lightweight data shippers).
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] The four products are designed for use together as the Elastic Stack.
[src:grafana-loki/elasticsearch] The combination was previously known as the ELK Stack, an initialism for "Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana".
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Torkel Odegaard released Grafana in January 2014 as an outgrowth of work on Graphite (software) at Orbitz.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] The user interface was originally based on version 3 of Kibana.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] The company behind the project, initially named Raintank, rebranded as Grafana Labs and has raised over $500 million in venture capital funding, reaching a $6 billion valuation in 2024.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Since 2021, Grafana has been licensed under the AGPLv3 (previously Apache 2.0).
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Grafana Labs provides two commercial Grafana offerings: Grafana Cloud for managed deployments and Grafana Enterprise for self-managed environments.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Grafana Cloud provides hosted Grafana, managed telemetry services, and additional capabilities such as Adaptive Telemetry for telemetry optimization and Grafana Assistant for AI-assisted observability workflows.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Grafana Enterprise contains features including LDAP team synchronization, data source permissions, and reporting.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Grafana was first released in January 2014, initially targeting Graphite and InfluxDB as data sources.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] It later added support for relational databases including MySQL, PostgreSQL, and Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Grafana Labs was founded in 2014 as Raintank and later adopted the name, Grafana, which combines Graphite and Kibana.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] The company raised $24 million in Series A funding in 2019, $50 million in Series B in 2020, $220 million in Series C in 2021 (at a $3 billion valuation), and $270 million in 2024 at a $6 billion valuation.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Grafana's backend is written in Go and its frontend in TypeScript using React.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] The application runs as a single binary that serves a web interface and connects to external data sources through a plugin system.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Plugins fall into three categories: data source plugins (for querying backends), panel plugins (for visualization types), and app plugins (for bundled functionality).
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Grafana does not store metrics data itself.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] It queries external data sources at render time and can combine data from multiple sources in a single dashboard.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Built-in data source support includes Prometheus, Graphite, InfluxDB, Elasticsearch, OpenSearch, Loki, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and Splunk.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Dashboards are defined as JSON documents and can be provisioned from files, version-controlled, and shared via Grafana's public dashboard library.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Alerting rules can be defined against any data source, with notifications routed to email, Slack, PagerDuty, and other channels.
[src:grafana-loki/grafana] Grafana is used by Wikimedia's infrastructure, NASA, and the Tour de France (for real-time race telemetry).
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Loki is a horizontally scalable, highly available, multi-tenant log aggregation system inspired by Prometheus.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] It’s designed to be very cost-effective and easy to operate.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] It doesn’t index the contents of the logs, but rather a set of labels for each log stream.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Note that the entire content of the log line is searchable, using labels just makes searching more efficient by narrowing the number of logs retrieved during querying.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Because all Loki implementations are unique, the installation process is different for every customer.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] But there are some steps in the process that are common to every installation.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Deploy Grafana Alloy to collect logs from your applications.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Add labels to your logs following our best practices.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Most Loki users start by adding labels that describe where the logs are coming from such as region, cluster, or environment.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Deploy Grafana or Grafana Cloud and configure a Loki data source.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Select the Explore feature in the Grafana main menu.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Use LogQL in the query editor, use the Builder view to explore your labels, or select from sample pre-configured queries using the **Kick start your query** button.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] To deploy Grafana Alloy to collect Pod logs from your Kubernetes cluster and ship them to Loki, you can use a Helm chart, and a `values.yaml` file.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Deploy Grafana Alloy using the Helm chart.
[src:grafana-loki/latest-get-started] Refer to Install Grafana Alloy on Kubernetes for more information.
[src:grafana-loki/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:grafana-loki/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:grafana-loki/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:grafana-loki/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:grafana-loki/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:grafana-loki/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:grafana-loki/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:grafana-loki/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:grafana-loki/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Grafana Loki is a set of open source components that can be composed into a fully featured logging stack.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] A small index and highly compressed chunks simplifies the operation and significantly lowers the cost of Loki.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Unlike other logging systems, Loki is built around the idea of only indexing metadata about your logs’ labels (just like Prometheus labels).
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Log data itself is then compressed and stored in chunks in object stores such as Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3) or Google Cloud Storage (GCS), or even locally on the filesystem.
