[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Select one or more clients to use to send your logs to Loki.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Learn how to manage tenants, log ingestion, storage, queries, and more.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Inspired by PromQL, LogQL is Grafana Loki’s query language.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] LogQL uses labels and operators for filtering.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Here are answers to some frequently asked questions about how to configure and run Loki.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Loki’s indexing model differs significantly from other observability products.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Choosing the wrong fields as labels is the most common cause of poor query performance and high resource usage.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Loki’s Explore Logs feature uses a `service_name` label to group and navigate logs.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] If it shows `unknown_service`, Loki could not automatically determine a service name from the incoming stream.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] If a `service_name` label is already present on the stream, Loki uses it directly.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] You can customize the list of labels Loki checks by setting `discover_service_name` in `limits_config`.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] A 429 error from Loki means an ingestion rate limit has been hit.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Loki enforces limits both globally and per-stream.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] If you are self-hosting and consistently hitting limits with legitimate log volume, increase the values above in `limits_config`.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] If you are on Grafana Cloud, contact support to adjust your plan limits.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] When Grafana and Loki run as separate Docker containers, `localhost` inside the Grafana container refers to the Grafana container itself, not the host machine or the Loki container.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] This is the most common misconfiguration for new users.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] In Grafana’s datasource settings, use `http://loki:3100` (the Docker Compose service name) instead of `http://localhost:3100`.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] If this returns `ready`, the networking is correct and the issue lies in the Grafana datasource configuration itself.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] This error occurs when the number of concurrent queries to Loki exceeds the configured limit for a tenant.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] It is most common when a dashboard has four or more panels querying over a long time range against a single-node (monolithic) deployment.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Splitting queries by interval reduces the load per request by breaking large time-range queries into smaller parallel chunks.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] If the issue persists at scale, consider moving from a monolithic deployment to microservices mode.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] By default, LogQL metric queries return no data points for intervals where no log lines matched, rather than returning `0`.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] This breaks percentage calculations and alert rules that expect a numeric baseline.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] Retention in Loki is handled by the **Compactor**, not by the ingester or storage backend directly.
[src:grafana-loki/loki-latest] To verify the Compactor is running and retention is active, check the Loki logs for lines referencing `compactor` and look for the metrics `loki_boltdb_shipper_compact_tables_operation_total` (compaction runs) and `loki_compactor_apply_retention_operation_total` (retention runs).
